<p>GE.12-12275  (E)    200312    200312 
</p>
<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Nineteenth session 
</b>Agenda item 10 
<b>Technical assistance and capacity-building 
</b></p>
<p><b>  President&#8217;s statement 
</b></p>
<p><b>  19/&#8230; 
Situation of human rights in Haiti 
</b></p>
<p> At the nineteenth session of the Human Rights Council, held from 27 February to  
23 March 2012, during consideration of agenda item 10, entitled &#8220;Technical assistance and 
capacity-building&#8221;, the President of the Council made the following statement: 
</p>
<p> 1. The Human Rights Council welcomes the latest legal and political 
developments in Haiti, marked notably by the appointment of 11 of the 12 judges of 
the Court of Cassation, including its president. 
</p>
<p> 2. The Council also welcomes the Haitian authorities&#8217; plans to build 
housing for victims of the 12 January 2010 earthquake. It further welcomes the 
establishment of a special fund for children&#8217;s schooling in Haiti. 
</p>
<p> 3. The Council applauds the reaffirmation of the Haitian authorities&#8217; 
commitment and determination to improve the living conditions of Haitian women 
and men, including by paying greater attention to respect for human rights. 
</p>
<p> 4. The Council also applauds the priorities set by the President of the 
Republic, which include the rule of law, education, the environment and 
employment, and urges donors to honour their commitments without delay. 
</p>
<p> 5. The Council is aware of the many obstacles to development in Haiti 
and of the difficulties encountered by its leaders in the daily governance of the 
country. It recognizes that the full enjoyment of human rights &#8212; both civil and 
political and economic, social and cultural &#8212; is a factor in peace, stability and 
progress in Haiti. 
</p>
<p> 6. The Council encourages the international community as a whole, and 
in particular international donors, the Group of Latin American and Caribbean 
States, the countries known as the Friends of Haiti, and United Nations specialized 
agencies, to step up their cooperation with the Haitian authorities for the full 
realization of human rights. 
</p>
<p> United Nations A/HRC/19/L.32
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>General Assembly </b>Distr.: Restricted 
19 March 2012 
English 
Original: French </p>


<p><b>2</b> GE.12-12275 
</p>
<p> 7. The Council welcomes the request of the Haitian authorities to have 
the mission of the independent expert on the situation of human rights in Haiti 
extended by one year until March 2013, and decides to approve this request. 
</p>
<p> 8. The Council requests the independent expert to work with 
international institutions, donors and the international community with a view to 
their providing expertise and sufficient resources to support the Haitian authorities&#8217; 
efforts to rebuild the country. 
</p>
<p> 9. The Council invites the independent expert to draw on his experience 
and expertise to further the cause of human rights in Haiti, with particular emphasis 
on economic, social and cultural rights. 
</p>
<p> 10. The Council also invites the independent expert to pursue his mission 
in Haiti and to report thereon to the Council at its twenty-third session. It encourages 
the Haitian authorities to cooperate fully with the independent expert. 
</p>
<p>    </p>

